// SPDX-License-Identifier: Apache-2.0 WITH LLVM-exception
//
// test/preprocess/p11/pass.test — P11 one-line directive limit per
// `docs/spec/nsl_pp.ebnf` notes section + the contract topic table
// in
// `specs/002-m1-lex-preprocess/contracts/preprocessor-seam.contract.md`.
//
// Topic per the table: "one-line directive limit: `#define X` ends
// at newline".
//
// P11 narrower-than-C semantics: a preprocessor directive ends at
// the end-of-line, regardless of any trailing `\` (backslash-line-
// continuation is **NOT** supported). In C this:
//
//   #define LONG \
//     1 + 2
//
// would be one logical line of `#define LONG  1 + 2`. In NSL P11
// disallows that — the trailing `\` is part of the body, not a
// continuation.
//
// Pass shape (this fixture): a `#define X` on one line, with body
// `1`. The next line is a separate logical line of NSL source.
// The macro X expands to integer `1` at the use site.
//
// Tasks.md T047. Fail-case is N/A — there's nothing to "violate"
// at source level beyond the documented continuation-not-supported
// behavior; an implementer who incorrectly handles a trailing `\`
// produces an obviously-wrong macro body that downstream fixtures
// catch.
//
// **RED state**: the unchanged Phase-3 lexer tokenizes the
// `#define X 1` bytes literally. Phase-4 turns it green.

// RUN: echo '#define X 1' >  %t.nsl
// RUN: echo 'reg y = %%X%%;' >> %t.nsl
// RUN: %nslc -emit=tokens %t.nsl | FileCheck %s

// X expands to integer 1; the line is treated as one directive.
// CHECK:      tk_reg{{[ \t]+}}reg
// CHECK-NEXT: tk_identifier{{[ \t]+}}y
// CHECK-NEXT: tk_assign{{[ \t]+}}=
// CHECK-NEXT: tk_decimal_lit{{[ \t]+}}1
// CHECK-NEXT: tk_semicolon{{[ \t]+}};
// CHECK-NEXT: tk_eof
